At Zhejiang University’s Academic Annual Conference, students took center stage; research findings were truly mind-blowing – Xinhua News Agency
Using air to wash hands, diagnosing diseases by exhaling, and precisely identifying the sources of smog – all these innovative academic achievements were recognized last night at the opening ceremony of Zhejiang University’s 2016 Academic Annual Conference.
The main researchers behind these achievements are all students, and their research covers a wide range of fields including environment, mechanics, energy, medicine, life sciences, and humanities education. Starting from a simple, curious idea, the students have created many high-quality inventions with practical applications, some of which have won awards both domestically and
Biosensors: Your Personal Health Check-Up Doctors at Home
The team led by Dr. Zhang Diming from the School of Biomedical Engineering demonstrated a biosensor for use on smartphones, which is only half the size of a typical smartphone.
All you need to do is take a gentle breath, and this device will be able to preliminarily assess your health condition based on the components of the air you exhale.
Zhang Diming explained that this set of sensors is connected to a smartphone, and after exhaling, a health report will be displayed on the phone.
Smart wristbands available on the market that can detect health conditions generally measure physical parameters such as temperature and pulse.
This set of biosensors employs graphene, a novel material, with chemical elements as their target. Their keen “sense of smell” allows them to provide a more in-depth and accurate reflection of the body’s health status.
Intelligent Surgical Lights: The Doctor’s High-Energy Eyes
In addition to smartphones, smart surgical lights are also being used in operating rooms.
This invention won the silver award at the 44th International Invention Exhibition in Geneva, Switzerland, this year.
The teams of master's students Zhu Linjing and Shen Junfei from the School of Optoelectronic Science and Engineering have identified shortcomings in traditional surgical lights and developed a new approach, resulting in the invention of an intelligent LED surgical shadowless light.
The inadequate early detection and removal of many diseases are related to the lighting used in the doctors’ operating rooms.
Shen Junfei said that, for example, during early cancer screening, if doctors cannot clearly observe all tumor tissues in a timely manner, then the cancer cells may continue to spread later on.
This intelligent surgical lamp has four light discs that adjust the spectrum to enhance the differentiation of different tissues when illuminated.
During the surgical procedure, doctors can adjust the size of the light spot, brightness level, spectrum, color uniformity, and shadow-free rate at any time, according to the needs of the surgery and the individual patient's preferences.
This intelligent surgical lighting system has already been tested in hospitals such as Sir Run Run Shaw Hospital affiliated with Zhejiang University School of Medicine and Children’s Hospital affiliated with Zhejiang University School of Medicine, and has received positive feedback.
Last October, this invention won the first prize in the National Challenge Cup.
Washing hands with air: saves water and looks cool too!
Ordinary people wash their hands by simply running water over them, at most using some soap or hand sanitizer, while students like Li Qizhang have invented a “handwashing device that uses air”.
As long as we stand on the handwashing station of the device, our weight can compress the air and force it out.
“It’s just like a pump.”
The compressed air forms a fluid at the faucet and combines with the water.
In this way, we can wash our hands clean!
Color development reactions and bacterial residue tests have proven that the effectiveness of handwashing using this method is the same as that of conventional handwashing methods.
This device relies solely on gravity as its driving force, ensuring thorough cleaning while saving 90% of water usage. Moreover, the entire process is completely energy-free, making it both environmentally friendly and energy-efficient.
Last year, at the second Global Major Challenges Summit, this invention stood out among many of the world’s top universities and won the only gold award.
