Let me start with the conclusion: In my personal opinion, “The Four Seas” is a completely terrible movie in every sense.
But if you say this movie has no highlights at all, that wouldn’t be quite right; at least the soundtrack is quite good.
There are many types of bad movies; those that make you fall asleep soundly in the cinema are one category, and those that leave you filled with indignation after watching are another. “The Four Seas” is like the monkeys on Mount Emei to the audience—it can ignite your anger in countless ways.
In terms of insulting the audience, Han Han truly has an extraordinary talent.
The most painful aspect of this film is that it seems to be a creation out of a Kafkaesque novel—indescribable and riddled with flaws, just like the trench coat worn by the character Marco.
Even after watching it, you might wonder if there are any hidden metaphors intended by the director, but upon further reflection, you realize it’s actually just a pile of shit.
Let me first briefly explain some plot elements that I find really difficult to understand.
The male protagonist lives on a small island in the southern region, relying on his grandmother for support.
Her grandmother had a wish to see snow, so the plot arranged for an elderly man from the neighborhood to drive her there in a small van to the northeast to see the snow.
Are elderly people traveling from the south to the northeast in a van just to see the snow???
He and his dad are still very reassured about this.
And then that old man’s story just ends there, with no further development.
How did the female protagonist’s brother obtain the business license to open a hotel on an abandoned ship?
Why are those little biker gang hooligans on the island able to easily block off a section of the mountain road??
Then the truck delivering steel rebar in the middle of the road stopped by the side of the road, and not even the truck driver could be found anywhere in the vicinity.
The sense that it’s just a prop is too obvious, isn’t it?
How could a small-time thug with a poor credit record and suspected involvement in illegal activities become an auxiliary police officer?
Why don’t they call the police when facing usury? In the movie, the police even specifically ask if there are any difficulties.
An adult knows how to use a smartphone, yet doesn’t know how to open a hotel room door with a key card. Unable to find the hotel owner, they end up sleeping outside the room door for the night?
These utterly inexplicable plot elements permeate the entire film, and due to their absurdity, recalling them still causes me great pain.
Apart from the plot, what’s even worse is the film’s lack of a real theme; in other words, the movie simply doesn’t have any coherent theme at all, and is nothing but a repulsive, disjointed mess.
At the beginning of the movie, you might think it’s a comedy. After about 20 minutes, you might guess it could be an inspirational film. Halfway through, you start to think it might be a drama depicting the hardships faced by young people in a small town. By the end, however, you
For most people, the tropes of various movies are actually quite familiar. For example, if you want to make a movie about a motorcycle rider, it usually involves a combination of inspirational and comedic elements, showing how a talented newcomer gradually achieves success step by step.
If you want to make a love movie, then just honestly tell the story of the complicated relationships between a young guy from the town who likes riding motorcycles and a waitress girl.
If you want to reflect reality, then at the very least your plot cannot contain anything that contradicts the normal world.
(For example, like the character played by Yoon Jung whose new motorcycle got burned down, yet he can still sing…) One shouldn’t come up with some utterly wild ideas that even Kennedy couldn’t stand.
As for the female protagonist who clearly isn’t mentally challenged but behaves in some ways like a 5-year-old child, I really don’t know whether it’s due to her acting skills or the director’s requirements.
There’s another thing I really can’t understand: Why is Han Han, as a racing driver, so keen on including car crash scenes in his own movies?
Is such a movie arrangement during the Spring Festival season simply meant to cause trouble for the audience?
