Chongqing’s secondary vocational schools are piloting a modern apprenticeship system; upon enrollment, students become quasi-employees of the companies – Xinhua News Agency
Yesterday, journalists learned from the Municipal Education Commission that starting this year, our city will pilot the “modern apprenticeship system” talent training model in 60 secondary vocational schools. Students participating in this pilot program will have both the status of apprentices, and after enrollment, they will be pre-employed as employees by the participating
The Municipal Education Commission has required the standardization of enrollment and admission procedures for secondary vocational schools and employment procedures for enterprises. It is necessary to clarify the dual identity of apprentices, who are both students at secondary vocational schools and prospective employees of enterprises. In accordance with the principle of mutual selection, apprentices, schools, and enterprises
Encourage pilot schools to adopt modern apprenticeship models and collaborate with enterprises to carry out pre-employment training and retraining for employees.
Pilot schools should reform the talent cultivation model.
Schools and enterprises jointly design talent training programs, jointly formulate professional teaching standards, curriculum standards, job standards, standards for enterprise mentors, quality monitoring standards, and corresponding implementation plans.
The pilot program is designed to last for one academic cycle, and the duration of students' internships in enterprises is determined according to the professional talent training programs, with a typical internship period of six months.
In corporate practices, a team-based management model should be implemented. Depending on the characteristics of different professions, one master can guide 2 to 5 apprentices to form learning groups, ensuring that students master the skills required for each training position proficiently.
According to the plan, from 2016 to August 2019, our city identified 60 pilot projects for the modern apprenticeship system at the municipal level in three batches. Each pilot project involved around 50 participants, resulting in the training of approximately 3,000 students
Following the principle of piloting first and then implementing, and progressing gradually from point to area, efforts should be made to establish a long-term mechanism for joint enrollment, joint training, and integrated education between schools and enterprises. This will effectively enhance students' job-related skills, increase their employment rate in relevant fields, and improve
