Xinhua All Media + | Beijing Youth Ice Hockey League Fuels Enthusiasm for the Winter Olympics - Xinhua News Agency
On December 11th, Pang Yaotian (center), a player from the Beijing DreamING team, took a shot during the match.
On that day, the 2021-2022 Beijing Youth Ice Hockey Club League continued to compete at various ice rinks in Beijing.
This league season is divided into a regular competition and a playoff phase, with participants ranging in age from U6 to U18. The teams are categorized into a competitive group and a selection group, attracting nearly 3,600 players from 256 representative teams across the city.
After more than a decade of development, the Beijing Youth Ice Hockey Club League has become a platform for young ice hockey enthusiasts in Beijing to exchange skills and make new friends. It also serves as a source of outstanding players for Beijing's youth ice hockey teams and the national junior teams.
The league competitions have played a significant role in promoting ice hockey among young athletes in Beijing, fueling the enthusiasm for ice hockey during the Winter Olympics and laying the foundation for the development of ice hockey in Beijing in the post-Olympic period.
Girl acts as target for arrows to raise money for her sister: “It’s still bearable when I think it’s just a superficial injury” – Xinhua News Agency
In Hangzhou’s Wulin Square, a girl stood in front of a large wooden board that read, “Human target; ten yuan per arrow.”
Yesterday morning, a photo of a girl from Hangzhou willingly acting as a “target” to raise funds for her sister went viral on social media.
The photo shows a girl in Hangzhou’s Wulin Square standing in front of a large wooden board that is slightly taller than her. On the board is written “Human target, ten yuan per arrow,” indicating that passersby can use a bow and arrow to shoot the target after paying.
This behavior has sparked heated discussions among netizens.
Last night, a spokesperson from the Xiacheng Branch of the Hangzhou Public Security Bureau confirmed to a reporter from The Beijing News that the police took such extreme measures because they believed the girl was raising funds for her sister. However, such behavior is not advisable. After being reprimanded, the girl left the local
Girl used as “target” on the street to raise funds; the defendant was warned
In the picture circulating online, a girl with long hair is standing in a “V” shape in front of a large wooden board. On the board, the words “Human target; 10 yuan per arrow” are written in black ink. On another board in front of her, her bank account number, as
The image sparked controversy after being posted online.
Some netizens believe that this is an “attention-seeking begging behavior,” while many others express sympathy for it.
“We discovered this situation around 10 a.m. on the 23rd while patrolling near the square; there were already quite a number of onlookers at that time.”
In an interview with local media, police officers from the Tianshui Police Station near the incident site stated that there were two girls setting up stalls, both around 20 years old and dressed in a youthful and attractive manner.
Among them, the girl who was used as a “human target” kept crying, begging passersby to play this game; another girl stood by, helping to spread the message that her friend’s sister had leukemia and urgently needed surgery funds, asking everyone for their help.
We contacted the local police in Guizhou and learned that the girl was raising funds for her sister’s leukemia treatment.
Last night, a person in charge of publicity at the Xiacheng Branch of the Hangzhou Public Security Bureau told a reporter from The Beijing News that the girl’s name is Jijiali, and she was collecting donations for her sister Ji Jiayan.
However, since the treatment still requires over 300,000 yuan in costs, and no good way to raise the funds could be thought of immediately, such an action was taken.
He said that throughout the entire process, one of the two girls served as a ‘target’ while the other acted as an assistant but did not actually participate in the shooting. No one was observed shooting arrows; instead, some people just watched and took photos, which were then posted on Weibo.
Subsequently, after appraisal by the public security department, it was determined that the bow and arrows used did not fall under the category of items subject to regulation.
The person in charge stated, “Such attention-grabbing fundraising methods are not advocated.”
After being warned by the police officers at the police station, she has left the station.
