What was the hottest thing in 2021?
There’s no doubt it’s the Tokyo Olympics.
Do you think only Olympic athletes can win awards?
Some time ago, an article titled “Look! Project Managers Can Compete in Olympic Events for Gold Medals” became very popular. It mentioned that project managers are definitely unmatched in many projects: carrying heavy burdens, traveling on business, and staying up late are part of their daily routine, while stepping in to solve problems
An article that seems like a joke or teasing actually reveals the daily hardships faced by project managers, reflecting the sense of powerlessness in current project management practices.
And those engaged in project management are also gradually choosing to take certain actions to help themselves out of the difficulties at work.
Judging from the increasing number of applicants for the PMP (Project Management Professional) certification each year, it is evident that more and more project management practitioners are improving their project management skills through learning.
According to the “China Project Management: Twenty Years of Development Report (1999-2019), as of September 2019, the cumulative number of people who registered for the PMP® exam nationwide was nearly 600,000, with approximately 420
In the past 10 years, the number of PMP-certified professionals has been increasing year by year, indicating that an growing number of project managers have realized that relying solely on traditional methods and past “experiences” is no longer viable. The rapidly changing work environment forces us to learn from the achievements of those
However, does obtaining the PMP certification guarantee that project management work will proceed smoothly without any obstacles?
Many beginners in project management claim that by studying courses such as PMP/IPMP, they can systematically master the ten key areas and five process groups of project management. Yet, when it comes to actually undertaking project management work, they still find themselves utterly confused.
Many project managers often face the following challenges: inadequate understanding of project management principles, reliance on personal experience alone, possession of theoretical knowledge but no practical application; lack of systematic project management processes and support mechanisms, leading to inaccurate project forecasts, poor control, and frequent project delays; unclear division of responsibilities among team members, with
