This year, during the “Double Eleven” shopping festival, the total amount of transactions in online payment services across the country reached 1.77 trillion yuan, setting a new record compared to previous years.
The diverse range of promotional offers, coupled with eye-catching live-streaming sales events, have once again allowed consumers to feel that they are getting a great deal. On one hand, this surge in consumption highlights the growing purchasing power of the nation; on the other hand, it also forces us to calmly consider the impact of
On the eve of “Double Twelve,” Joyoung Consumer Finance Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as “Joyoung”) issued a call for rational consumption, reminding users, especially young people, to develop good consumption awareness and habits, and to reject blind and excessive spending.
According to the results of the “Consumer Financial Literacy Survey and Analysis Report” released by the People’s Bank of China this year, the national consumer financial literacy index is 66.81, which represents an increase of 2.04 compared to 2019.
Overall, the residents of our country perform well in terms of financial consumption, but there are significant differences in various aspects of financial behavior and skills, indicating a need for further improvement in basic financial knowledge.
Given that the financial literacy levels of the elderly and teenagers are relatively low, these two groups will continue to be a focus of financial education efforts. According to Nielsen’s “Report on the Debt Status of Young People in China” and CCTV Finance’s “2019-2020 China Youth Consumption Report,”
