Twelve years after its inception, Bitcoin celebrated several milestone events in 2021.
On September 7th, El Salvador, a small country in Central America, designated Bitcoin as its official currency, marking the first time that Bitcoin has become the legal tender of a country or region.
On October 12th, for the first time in eight years, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) approved ProShares’ launch of a Bitcoin ETF, which was then listed on the New York Stock Exchange. This marks the debut of the first compliant Bitcoin ETF on the U.S. capital market
From the perspective of blockchain technology development, Bitcoin is not the main protagonist.
On November 14, 2021, Bitcoin underwent a soft fork upgrade known as “Taproot.” This upgrade enhanced the anonymity of transactions on the Bitcoin network and reduced the data burden associated with transactions by altering the data structure of the blocks themselves.
