Asian-American groups have complained of discriminatory admissions practices at three Ivy League universities, including Yale – Xinhua News Agency
Xinhua News Agency, Washington, May 23 (Reporter Xu Jianmei) On May 23, more than 130 Asian-American organizations submitted a complaint to the U.S. Department of Education and the Department of Justice, protesting against discrimination against Asian-American applicants in the admissions processes at three
The Asian Education Alliance, which initiated the complaint, held a press conference in Washington on the same day.
Zhao Yukong, the chairman of the group, said at the press conference that in the past 10 years, the number of Asian applicants who meet the admission criteria of top American universities has increased significantly, but among these three prestigious American universities, the proportion of Asians has remained relatively constant.
Many studies have shown that these universities systematically and persistently discriminate against Asian applicants during what is known as the “comprehensive evaluation” admissions process.
Zhao Yukong explained that research by scholars such as Sanders in 2014 showed that among these three universities, the acceptance rate for Asians was the lowest among all ethnic groups, relative to the number of applicants.
Data from the U.S. Department of Education also shows that among all Ivy League schools, Brown University and Dartmouth College have the lowest acceptance rates for Asian students. Yale University and Brown University have implemented de facto racial quotas for Asian applicants for over 20 years.
Zhao Yukong told Xinhua News Agency reporters that they hope that after submitting the appeal, the U.S. Department of Education and the Department of Justice will conduct an investigation and take measures to prevent these universities from continuing to discriminate against Asian students in admissions.
They also expect that the universities that have been complained about will take this issue seriously on their own initiative and change their admissions policies towards Asian students.
So far, the three universities that have received complaints have not yet responded.
The Asian Education Alliance was established in 2015 and had previously filed a complaint against Harvard University for discriminatory admissions practices, but the U.S. Department of Education dismissed the complaint on procedural grounds.
In addition to Chinese-American groups participating in this appeal, there were also educational organizations representing Indian Americans, Korean Americans, Japanese Americans, and Pakistani Americans.
