In Sabah, 3,200 newborn babies did not receive their birth certificates due to a shortage of specially manufactured anti-counterfeiting paper.
(11th November, Kuching) The Sabah National Registration Office reported that due to the depletion of stock of special anti-counterfeiting paper, birth registration certificates have not been issued for newborn babies since early October. To date, a total of 3,200 people have been affected by this
However, the director of the bureau, Keruaminus, assured that all the information of the babies who have already applied for birth registration papers has been recorded in the system, and the papers will be reissued once the anti-counterfeiting materials arrive next week.
At a press conference, he responded to a report by an online media outlet regarding issues with the printing of newspaper paper in Sabah that had persisted for up to 10 months.
He said that the relevant issues had emerged two months ago, and Sarawak was also facing the same problems.
One of the reasons is that Chinese manufacturers producing special anti-counterfeiting paper have been affected by the pandemic, resulting in delays in its delivery to our country.
He explained that the anti-counterfeiting paper used in Sabah’s newspaper production is different from that used in other regions, and therefore it is not possible to borrow stock from other states.
Keruaminus revealed that the latest batch of anti-counterfeiting paper arrived in Kuala Lumpur on the 6th of this month and was then handed over to the printing company on the 8th for partial printing.
“The department will send someone to Kuala Lumpur next Thursday to pick up the goods. Upon returning to Sabah, the final printing stages will be carried out immediately. It is estimated that the goods can be delivered to the applicants by December 20, which is about two more working days.”
1. “We will inform the applicants to go to the local branches to collect the birth registration forms.”
He added that Sabah has issued a total of 24,801 birth registration certificates so far this year.
