Don’t scare people into collapsing at the starting line – Xinhua News Agency
When visiting book fairs, it's often possible to sense the popularity of books on success and self-improvement.
Many of today's success books promote the “best-principle” approach: they begin by assuming or implying that you have the ability to achieve your goals, and only then tell you what you need to do to accomplish them.
In other words, it’s as if we’re skipping right over the most important and fundamental step of “how to do it.”
For this very reason, these books all share a common characteristic: either you go all in and do your best, or you don’t do anything at all; it’s either 100 or 0; either you climb Mount Tai, or you just stay put where you are.
This “best principle,” which anyone looking at it would agree is absolutely correct, will still scare 99% of people into backing down before they even have a chance to try to implement it.
Because this theory advocates the idea of “you need to make a firm decision to change completely and undergo a 180-degree transformation,” and this is precisely what many people’s greatest weakness is.
For those who are rigid, conservative, and resistant to change, trying to shout in their ears “You need to change” is undoubtedly a form of self-deception and like talking to a stone.
The vast majority of people become hesitant in the face of the word “change,” holding back and struggling to make up their minds. Alternatively, some may make a hasty decision to change on a whim and bravely take the first step, but often the good results don’t last long, and they give up after a
Mr. Ma Sanli’s famous cross-talk performance “Starting from Tomorrow” is a classic example that vividly illustrates this “universal human nature.”
The biggest problem with the “Best Principle” is that its threshold is too high; it often exceeds the capabilities of ordinary people, leaving the vast majority of them feeling discouraged and unable to pursue it.
Perhaps, the “second-best principle” is the approach that has the greatest potential for helping more ordinary people on their way to relative success.
The core of the “second-best principle” lies in “lowering the threshold” – it encourages the idea of accumulating small victories to achieve a larger one. In other words, if you can’t achieve 100%, it’s okay to achieve even just 1%; after all, 1 is always greater
In short, as long as you do something, it’s always better than not doing anything at all.
With the threshold significantly lowered, there are more possibilities for ordinary people to persevere, and whenever one perseveres, the chances of success also increase.
The path to success by following the “second-best principle” is just a bit longer.
In summary, although the “best principle” ostensibly aims to help everyone succeed, it ultimately motivates only a minority of people; it is the “second-best principle” that can effectively motivate a larger number of individuals and bring benefits to as many people as possible.
