The reserves of naked carp in Qinghai Lake have increased by 7,100 tons this year – Xinhua News Agency
Xinhua News Agency, Xining, December 11 (Reporters Luo Xiaofei, Zhang Hongxiang) Reporters learned from the Qinghai Provincial Department of Agriculture and Rural Affairs that the latest monitoring results show that the reserves of naked carp in Qinghai Lake have increased by 7,10
The Qinghai Lake naked carp, commonly known as "Huang fish," is a unique and precious species found only in Qinghai Lake. It plays a crucial role in maintaining the safety of the "water-fish-bird" ecological chain and biodiversity within the Qinghai Lake basin.
In the 1960s and 1970s, affected by factors such as extensive human hunting and the deteriorating environmental conditions in the breeding areas of the Gymnocyprinus przewalskii, the population of the naked carp in Qinghai Lake plummeted. By 20
In 2004, the Qinghai Lake naked carp was listed as an endangered species in the “China Species Red List”.
Since 2003, Qinghai Province has implemented a policy of closing lakes for fish conservation, prohibiting any unit, collective, or individual from fishing for naked carp in Qinghai Lake and its main rivers and tributaries, as well as prohibiting the sale of naked carp and its products.
Meanwhile, through measures such as artificial propagation and release, cleaning of the main rivers flowing into Qinghai Lake, and designing scientifically sound “fish passages,” conservation efforts have been continuously intensified, resulting in an annual increase in the reserves of the naked carp population in Qinghai Lake.
Yang Lin, deputy director of the Qinghai Provincial Department of Agriculture and Rural Affairs, introduced that as of now, nearly 180 million Qinghai Lake naked carp have been artificially propagated and released into the lake, contributing more than 23% to the recovery of the naked carp population there.
The Sanjiangyuan region in Qinghai is an important ecological barrier and water conservation area for both China and Asia, while Qinghai Lake serves as a natural barrier and ecological functional area that prevents the desertification in the west from spreading eastward.
In order to protect the ecological environment of the Sanjiangyuan region and Qinghai Lake, as well as aquatic wildlife and to maintain the biodiversity of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, Qinghai has successively issued notices prohibiting fishing in key waters of the Yangtze River, Yellow River, and Qinghai
