Just saw an article about menstruation; it was too long.
Let me give a brief explanation for men who may not know about this.
Most girls will suddenly experience their first menstrual period at some point between the ages of 13 and 15, and menopause occurs around the age of 50.
After that, assuming good health, it will occur fairly regularly once a month.
But it’s not predictable with such precision; there’s usually a margin of about a week, so you need to prepare in advance. Sometimes, bad luck can also cause things to go wrong (such as the event happening several days earlier than expected).
The duration, amount of bleeding, and severity of menstrual cramps vary from person to person. Some people experience them for three days, while others for a week; some have light bleeding, while others suffer from heavy bleeding; some people don’t experience any discomfort at all, while others are in such pain that they need
The menstrual flow is uncontrollable, with bleeding occurring 24 hours a day for several days from start to finish. The only option is to use sanitary pads or tampons to absorb the blood and prevent it from soiling clothes and chairs.
Menstrual cramps are mainly caused by the secretion of prostaglandins. If you take ibuprofen as soon as your period starts, before the cramps become severe, it can effectively relieve the pain for that month. Taking it after the cramps have already begun is not very effective.
Before menstruation, due to increased blood flow in the uterus and excessive release of prostaglandins, diarrhea is more likely to occur.
If it's around the time of my period and I suddenly have diarrhea for no apparent reason, my period usually starts within two days.
It’s best to change sanitary pads every two to three hours; otherwise, bacteria can easily grow. Excluding sleep time, in the worst-case scenario, you’d need to change them 6 times a day. With 7 days in a month, that amounts to 42 pads. If you also include some
Tampons don’t need to be changed frequently; changing them every five to six hours is usually sufficient, with a maximum of eight hours.
During menstruation, hormonal fluctuations can make one more irritable, and during ovulation, emotional instability may also arise due to changes in hormones within the body. It’s really unfortunate; it’s as if the body is deliberately creating its own obstacles for us.
However, official crime rate data indicates that women have a high ability to control their emotions and do not use emotional issues as excuses.
What is flowing is not just blood; it also contains the shed endometrium.
The endometrium is thinnest after menstruation and then gradually thickens. You can think of the uterus as a house; every month, it “builds” a new lining in preparation for a potential “guest” (the fertilized egg). If no guest arrives (i.e., no pregnancy occurs),
Menstruation can be extremely inconvenient. For decades, women have had to deal with bleeding for several days each month, 24 hours a day, in addition to experiencing abdominal and back pain. Who would want that?
But a person is born because his mother has had menstruation, which serves to prepare the body for the 10 months that the baby will spend in this world. Everyone should be grateful to their mothers for having regular and healthy menstrual cycles.
In the past, many aspects of women's lives were suppressed, and society brainwashed women into believing that certain behaviors were dirty and shameful. Everyone just accepted that as the truth, but times have changed.
If anyone finds menstruation disgusting, or thinks that the physical processes a woman’s body goes through in preparation for childbirth are repulsive, and dares to speak about it in public, then girls, stand up and stop thinking that way. You may never experience it yourself, and probably never will; and men, who
Finally, ladies, give tampons a try; they really work well.
