If your feet go numb while soaking in a foot bath tub, could it be due to an electrical leakage?
Choosing the right foot bath tub can play a significant role in foot therapy and health maintenance. Today, the editor from Gome will provide answers to this question, hoping it will be helpful to our friends.
As people's awareness of health and wellness increases, foot bath tubs have become increasingly popular among consumers. A wide range of products with different prices is available on the market, ranging from just over a hundred yuan to several thousand yuan, providing consumers with a great deal of choice.
According to relevant data, compared to traditional household appliances, health-related appliances such as foot baths are selling very well. However, since there are no specific industry standards for foot baths, there are certain safety risks involved.
“Soaking your feet in charged water is really too dangerous, isn’t it?”
Mr. Li told the reporter that recently, he bought a foot bath for his father as a birthday gift. However, when his father used it, he felt numbness in the soles of his feet.
At first, Mr. Li thought it was caused by the vibration function of the foot bath tub, but to his surprise, even after turning off the vibration function, his father still felt a tingling sensation in the soles of his feet.
Mr. Li tested it with a test pen, and to his surprise, the pen lit up. He then discovered that the water in the foot bath was actually electrically charged.
Later, he contacted the merchant, and although the merchant's attitude was quite good, Mr. Li still felt dissatisfied.
Because he found that there are no clear and detailed industry regulations regarding the currently popular foot bath tubs in terms of the highest temperature settings, suitable user groups, or the materials used to ensure safety.
However, in general, foot bath tubs do not have electrical issues, but it cannot be ruled out that a small number of products may not have undergone strict quality control before leaving the factory.
Therefore, when purchasing, choose a split-type foot bath tub.
With the separation of water and electricity, there are no safety hazards at all.
At the same time, you can use a stylus to test as you wish.
The 13th Provincial Tea Expo has opened – Video Highlights – Hunan Daily Online – Huasheng Online
This morning, the 13th Hunan Tea Industry Expo and Xinhua Black Tea Promotion Event were held at the Hunan International Convention and Exhibition Center. The event aimed to showcase the tea industry, promote innovative tea technologies, promote tea culture, and accelerate efforts towards achieving a tea industry worth 100
Hou Shunli, Deputy Director of the Council of the All-China Federation of Supply and Marketing Cooperatives, and Ye Hongzhuan, Deputy Director of the Standing Committee of the Provincial People's Congress, attended the opening ceremony.
At the opening ceremony, Professor Liu Zhonghua, an academician of the Chinese Academy of Engineering, proudly announced that the origin of Huhong tea lies in Xinhua, and the rise of black tea has injected new momentum into the development of “Wucai Xiangcha” (a variety of Hun
In recent years, the Provincial Party Committee and the Provincial Government have provided strong support for the development of the tea industry, promoting the construction of a tea industry worth hundreds of billions of yuan, and forming a development pattern known as “Three Hunan Regions, Four Types of Water, and Five Colorful Teas.”
The tea industry within the province has intensified its innovation efforts, with key tea varieties such as green tea, dark tea, and black tea taking turns to thrive. The main tea-producing areas have promoted the integration of tea production with tourism, thereby boosting the income of numerous tea farmers.
The cycle of fortune continues, and black tea is making a comeback once again.
Experts in the tea industry within the province say that by harvesting green tea, followed by black tea and dark tea, tea farmers can generate income throughout the year, and the value of tea plantations continues to rise steadily.
