Ding Zilin: To a friend.
I would like to express my heartfelt gratitude to all my friends for the humanitarian assistance they have provided over the more than 30 years since the loss of our loved one. This assistance has continued without interruption, especially since I personally issued a call for help to friends both at home and abroad in early 199
These days, the parents of the vast majority of the deceased have passed away, and their orphans have also grown up, started families, and found employment.
It was your acts of kindness that helped us, these families in distress, through the most difficult times.
Currently, as the COVID-19 pandemic rages around the world, most of the donors have also reached retirement age.
Therefore, I earnestly request you to cease making humanitarian donations to us—the Tiananmen Mothers group. This act of humanitarian assistance should have come to a perfect end a long time ago.
I will always remember your kindness, and I firmly believe that your righteous deeds will be remembered by history.
For various reasons, I can only express my wishes in this manner. Please understand, friends!
Please accept my sincere blessings.
Please allow me to take this opportunity to briefly introduce the 32-year history of humanitarian assistance work conducted by the International Federation of Chinese Students Associations (IFCSS) and the Minnesota China Democracy Foundation (MCDF).
In the process of providing humanitarian assistance, the All America Students United and the Minnesota China Democracy Foundation are two parallel organizations, with frequent overlap in the implementation of their projects.
(Apple Daily photo: The Tiananmen Mothers website is managed by Tao Ye.) pic.twitter.com/UxID9ZGjzm
Relief funds often fail to reach the hands of the victims of the June 4th incident smoothly.
In 1994, upon the suggestion of Teacher Ding, a special group was established by the “Tiananmen Mothers” to coordinate and be responsible for the receipt and distribution of humanitarian aid funds.
In 1998, MCDF established the “June 4 Orphans Education Fund.” After 11 years of operation, in 2009, once all the June 4 orphans had completed their university education, MCDF then established the “June 4 Orphaned and Elderly
The funding for these projects mainly comes from donations made on campus and in the community during the 1989 Tiananmen Square incident, from generous contributions from individuals, and with the support of the Democratic Foundation of sister universities.
Since 2018, it has also received support from the Labor Reform Research Foundation.
It was not until last year, after a wait of 31 years, that the survivors of the June 4th incident finally received a portion of the donations that had been collected in Hong Kong in their name back then.
During this period, “Chinese Human Rights” was also independently carrying out its humanitarian assistance projects.
We understand that Teacher Ding's decision to halt the donations was out of consideration for the donors. After all, we are all retired individuals whose incomes are not as substantial as they were before retirement. For this reason, we would like to express our gratitude for Teacher Ding's letter “To Friends”.
We will respect the decisions of the affected families, terminate this project within two years, and resume it immediately if necessary.
To all those fellow individuals who, for many years now, have consistently shown great generosity and risked their own safety to deliver humanitarian aid, my sincere thanks and respect go out to you.
