Chinese and Saudi curators jointly organize Saudi Arabia's first contemporary art biennial - Xinhua News Agency
Xinhua News Agency, Riyadh, December 12 (Reporters Wang Haizhou, Hu Guan) Saudi Arabia’s first contemporary art biennale, the Diriyah Contemporary Art Biennale, officially opened to the public on the 11th at the JAX Art District in Diriy
This biennial exhibition was jointly curated by the Saudi Diriyah Biennial Foundation and the UCCA (Ullens Center for Contemporary Art) in China, with Tian Feiyu, the director of UCCA, serving as the artistic director.
According to the curatorial team, the theme of this biennial exhibition is “Crossing the River by Feeling the Stones,” which metaphorically represents the reform strategies adopted during periods of socio-economic transformation and also reflects the current state of cultural development in Saudi society.
This biennial covers an area of nearly 12,000 square meters, with exhibition halls spread across six interconnected buildings. It is presented in six sections: “Crossing the River by Touching the Stones,” “Inheritance as an Experiment,” “Marginal Thinking,” “Reaching the Public,” “
Among them, the works of 27 Saudi artists account for more than 40% of the total exhibits in this show, encompassing various forms such as painting, installation art, and performance art; the works of 12 Chinese artists have also received much attention. Some Chinese artists use recycled materials in innovative
Buckley, the CEO of the Diriyah Biennial Foundation, stated that they hope this biennial will establish international dialogue, providing global audiences with the opportunity to learn about Saudi Arabia’s thriving cultural industry and creative communities, and strengthening interaction and exchange.
Tian Feiyu said, “The goal of the biennial is twofold: it aims to enable Saudi contemporary art to participate in the global dialogue, as well as to integrate Saudi audiences into the world of contemporary art.”
It is understood that a series of lectures will also be held during the opening week of the biennial, where artists, curators, and leading figures from the creative industry will discuss topics such as cross-cultural communication and the development of contemporary art.
