Moving further and further away from one’s ideals; even the dragon-slaying boy eventually turns into a evil dragon.
I think “left” and “right” generally refer to constraints and freedom. Due to the inherent cultural and historical factors, China as a whole tends to lean towards the “left.”
In the domestic context, the right-wing advocates for freedom and emphasizes efficiency and development, while the left-wing strengthens regulation and places more emphasis on fairness and security.
In today’s society, there is a general desire for greater emphasis on fairness. At the same time, with the ongoing rivalry between China and the United States, a left-leaning trend is quite evident and is expected to continue for many years to come.
Even though I don’t understand it, just giving a like will be enough.
I won’t say anything more; Hua Hua is just that kind of loyal and righteous person.
In the past two years, the US blockade and encirclement of Huawei’s chips have not only plunged Huawei into unprecedented difficulties but also caused huge losses for “American-owned” companies.
The United States' suppression of China's chip industry, by demanding that its own companies and those of its allied countries also impose sanctions on China's chip industry, has directly resulted in impacts on the orders and profits of global chip suppliers. This has led to reduced research and development investment by chip manufacturers and decreased production capacity,
Today, the "chip shortage" has affected various industries around the world, such as car manufacturers halting production and smartphone prices rising. Almost all industries that use chips have been severely impacted by this issue.
In order to gain control over chip autonomy, more and more countries' technology giants are starting to embark on a path of "de-romanticization."
In order to firmly maintain control over the global semiconductor industry and curb the development of China’s semiconductor sector, the United States has been quite active recently. They have hosted a “Chip Summit,” invited giants from 64 countries to form a semiconductor alliance, and provided funding to support American tech companies. For instance, Intel
When most people thought that Intel’s move would have a certain impact on TSMC and could very likely take away TSMC’s business.
I am so certain of this because Intel, as a long-established technology giant of the United States, has been deeply involved in the semiconductor industry for decades. It boasts a large pool of talented professionals and substantial technical reserves, which will surely enable it to rise rapidly in a short period of time and surpass TSMC.
However, regarding Intel’s decision, TSMC founder Terry Gou dismissed it as insignificant.
At the “2021 Masters Think Tank Forum” held in April this year, Terry Gou made a startling statement. Regarding Intel’s decision to invest in building a wafer factory, he spoke without hesitation: “It’s quite ironic that Intel is establishing a chip foundry.”
The reason why Zhang Zhongmou holds such disdain for Intel's entry into the wafer manufacturing industry is that he still harbors resentment over a conflict between TSMC and Intel that occurred over 30 years ago.
In the 1960s and 1970s, Intel was the crown jewel of American manufacturing, occupying a dominant position at the global forefront and ruling the semiconductor industry.
By the 1980s, high-end semiconductor chips around the world were still in the hands of a few dominant companies.
At that time, the semiconductor industry was characterized by the IDM model, where the entire process from chip design, manufacturing to packaging and testing was carried out by a single company. Intel was the representative of that era.
However, such a model places a heavy burden on some small businesses, and many semiconductor entrepreneurs are deterred by the enormous costs associated with building production lines.
Inspired by market demand, the chip industry began to show signs of division of labor and cooperation in the 1980s. In 1984, Morris Chang learned about companies that specialized in chip design, and he realized that since such companies existed, it would be feasible to set up a factory
Not long after, Morris Chang's vision came to fruition, and TSMC was born.
TSMC has focused its main business on the single process of “wafer fabrication.” It does not engage in design but only provides contract manufacturing services for wafer production.
At that time, TSMC, which had just been established, was nothing but a tiny player in the face of the giant Intel.
In order to obtain capital support, Zhang Zhongmou approached Intel for investment. However, when Intel learned that TSMC was only involved in the manufacturing aspect of the chip industry, they were clearly quite arrogant and looked down on TSMC, thus decisively rejecting the investment proposal.
Jack Zhang also believed that Intel looked down on wafer manufacturing services at that time.
It’s surprising that the giants who used to look down on wafer manufacturing services are now also starting to engage in wafer foundry operations.
So, Zhang Zhongmou finds it ironic that Intel entered the wafer foundry business.
Today, TSMC's market value has surpassed that of Intel.
Faced with TSMC's strong offensive, Intel naturally cannot afford to stand still and become complacent.
Today, TSMC is already racing towards 3nm chips, while Intel is still stuck at the 14nm technology from 7 years ago.
Trying to catch up or surpass others is actually not that easy.
No more waiting.
