Starry Sky Appointment | The Geminid Meteor Shower Reaches Its Peak on the 14th - Xinhua News Agency
Xinhua News Agency, Tianjin, December 12 (Reporter Zhou Runjian) According to astronomy and popular science experts, the Geminid meteor shower, one of the three major meteor showers in the Northern Hemisphere and also the last large-scale meteor shower of the year, will reach its peak on December
The Geminid meteor shower was photographed by An Jiu, an astronomy enthusiast from Beijing, on December 13, 2018, in Qinghai.
The parent bodies of most meteor showers are periodic comets, but the parent body of the Geminid meteor shower is asteroid 3200 Phaethon, which is an Apollo-type asteroid.
The Geminid meteor shower is also the second known meteor shower that is not originated from a comet.
Xiu Lipeng, a director of the Tianjin Astronomical Society and an expert in popularizing astronomy, explained that, just like blockbuster New Year’s movies, the Geminid meteor shower generally appears at the end of the year, with its “showtime period” lasting from December 4th to December
This meteor shower is known for its high and steady rate of meteor appearances. Together with the Quadrantid meteor shower and the Perseid meteor shower, it is considered one of the three major meteor showers in the Northern Hemisphere.
A notable feature of the Geminid meteor shower is that the meteoroids move at a relatively slow speed, possess a rich variety of colors, and there are also many fireballs among them. This makes it ideal for both visual observation and for beginners in astrophotography to capture stunning images.
The Geminid meteor shower was photographed by Yang Jing, an astronomy enthusiast from Tianjin, on December 13, 2020, in Jizhou, Tianjin.
Astronomical forecasts indicate that this year’s Geminid meteor shower will reach its peak around 15:00 on December 14th, with a ZHR (Zenith Hourly Rate) of 150. The ZHR represents the number of meteors visible per hour under
Geminid Meteor Shower Recommendation Index Chart.
Last year, the “falling stars” of the Geminid meteor shower left a deep impression on people, but this year’s Geminid meteor shower will be affected by moonlight, and the spectacle might be a bit less impressive as a result.
The 14th corresponds to the 11th day of the 11th lunar month, during which the moon is in a waxing gibbous phase. The bright moonlight may interfere with observations. However, fortunately, the moon will set in the latter half of the night. At that time
Friends who enjoy meteor showers can observe them in the hours after the moon sets in the latter half of the night, but be sure to keep warm to avoid catching a cold.
How can one observe as many meteors as possible?
It is not recommended to conduct observations in urban areas. One can choose a location in the suburbs or countryside that is at a high altitude, has minimal light pollution, and offers a clear view in the northeast direction. Then, one should patiently wait for the moon to set before conducting the visual observation.
It’s important to note that the Geminid meteor shower has a high rate of meteors coming from various directions, so there’s no need to constantly focus on the radiant point of the shower during observation.
For photography enthusiasts who wish to capture stunning “meteor shower” photos, it is advisable to choose a wide-angle lens with a large aperture, and to use high ISO settings along with the maximum aperture of the lens during shooting.
Considering stability and durability, a tripod, spare batteries, and a shutter release cable are also essential.
Xiu Lipeng reminded them.
What are the differences in market positioning between laser TVs and traditional TVs?
As far as I understand, the so-called traditional TV mentioned by the questioner should refer to LCD TVs. The main differences in market positioning between laser TVs and LCD TVs are as follows:
Firstly, laser TVs are more focused on the large-screen market.
Compared to the widespread market positioning of LCD TVs, laser TVs are clearly more focused on the large-screen market. In other words, laser TVs are essentially products designed for large screens.
Currently, mainstream LCD TVs generally range in size from 55 to 65 inches, whereas laser TVs typically exceed 75 inches in size, with the largest models going over 100 inches, fully meeting users' demand for large-screen televisions.
In recent years, the shipment volume and sales share of laser TVs have been continuously increasing globally, accounting for over 60% of the total sales of TVs with a screen size of 80 inches and above.
According to the predictions of CIC Group, in 2020, the sales volume of laser TVs is expected to grow by more than 140%, continuing to maintain a high growth rate.
The reason for such excellent results in the large-screen market is mainly due to the outstanding performance of laser TVs in terms of eye protection.
Based on the principle of diffuse reflection in laser TVs, the light emitted by the laser source does not directly enter the eyes. Compared to the backlighting of liquid crystal TVs, the imaging process is closer to how objects are perceived under natural conditions, resulting in less irritation to the eyes.
Experts from the SICE Laboratory of the China Electronics Technology Standardization Institute and the Ophthalmology Department of Peking Union Medical College Hospital conducted a rigorous comparative experiment involving people watching laser TVs and LCD TVs under the same conditions, resulting in 144 sets of test data.
Data confirms that laser TVs indeed possess strong eye-protecting characteristics and can even have a certain improving effect in specific aspects.
In an era where vision health is receiving increasing attention, laser TVs have not only attracted more and more users due to their eye-protective advantages but have also opened up another breakthrough in the color TV market.
Secondly, laser TVs are more focused on the high-end market.
Contrary to the continuous decline in the prices of LCD TVs, the prices of laser TVs currently available on the market are mostly over 10,000 yuan. As the size and light source are upgraded, the prices are gradually increasing.
Why are laser TVs so expensive?
There must be some logic to it.
With the continuous advancement of light sources and technological levels, laser TVs possess many advantages that liquid crystal TVs and projectors are unable to achieve.
Thanks to their ultra-short-throw projection technology, laser TVs have a much shorter projection distance compared to traditional projection devices. This enables a 100-inch large-screen experience at a short distance, while requiring minimal space. Moreover, the main unit of the laser TV is compact and takes up very little room.
In terms of brightness, high-brand laser TVs can achieve over 2000 lumens.
Furthermore, with lower heat generation, there is less wear and tear on the equipment, resulting in a longer lifespan for the television.
In addition to this, many high-end laser TV models are also equipped with true 4K ultra-high-definition picture quality, artificial intelligence systems, bionic screens, and numerous other cutting-edge technologies, providing users with an even more stunning audio-visual experience.
It’s not so much a case of “pseudo-demand” as rather a product of more detailed market segmentation. In terms of image quality and cost-effectiveness, laser TVs are not the ideal choice for audio-visual enthusiasts. If you’re looking to combine a large screen with a suitable viewing environment but face certain limitations,
In simple terms, ultra-wide-angle, short-throw projectors—such as laser TVs—have to use expensive ultra-wide-angle lenses and mirrors in order to get the image close to the screen, which does not conform to the principles of optimal optical design.
In order to block some of the ambient light, using a microstructured Fresnel screen comes at a high cost; the price of an 80-inch screen is basically equivalent to that of a 65-inch LCD screen.
Another thing that really irritates me is when projector manufacturers use the claim that diffused light is better for the eyes as a selling point. Come on, the light from the screen that reaches our eyes is actually direct light. Even if that light is then diffused and bounces off the ceiling, our eyes can’t
Moreover, if the projection screen does not exhibit diffuse reflection, it simply cannot form an image.
It’s precisely the hot spot (light spot) effect of high-gain screens that is often overlooked. When a large amount of light is reflected into the eyes from a certain angle, that’s when it becomes truly uncomfortable.
