Is it reliable to buy insurance for a small umbrella?
Little Umbrella is an internet-based insurance brokerage platform.
Based on the "Regulations on the Supervision of Insurance Brokerage Firms (Revised in 2015)," there are three essential conditions that must be met to establish an insurance brokerage company: the shareholders and promoters must have no significant legal violations in the past three years, the minimum capital requirement is R
These three requirements are indeed quite stringent. In essence, a company must possess the necessary capabilities and obtain approval from the authoritative national regulatory body, the China Banking and Insurance Regulatory Commission (CBIRC), which oversees insurance companies and banks nationwide. The shareholders must also have a good reputation. As an insurance brokerage firm, Xiaoy
In this regard, it’s not bad at all; it’s trustworthy.
From the perspective of insurance products: Xiaoyusan Insurance functions as an “insurance supermarket,” where many well-known critical illness insurance policies from various companies are sold on this platform. For instance, the recently launched Hetai Super Mary 5 Critical Illness Insurance is offered by Hetai Life Insurance, which handles both
From the perspective of payment methods: Internet platform products have a higher cost-performance ratio because they eliminate the operational expenses of physical stores and employee salaries. They also offer flexible payment options, including monthly payments, which reduce the financial burden on policyholders. At the same time, this approach allows for maximum leverage of insurance benefits.
This is really quite good.
It can be considered.
From the perspective of the professionalism of sales representatives, this is particularly important because insurance is an industry that demands a high level of expertise. Many internet-based products allow customers to purchase insurance on their own, which can lead to numerous misunderstandings. When it comes to health declarations and occupations, individuals who are not from the insurance
I have personally worked in insurance telemarketing for “Tencent Weibao” (similar to Xiaoyusan, which is also an internet-based insurance brokerage platform), and I can tell you all very responsibly...
Insurance on the internet is indeed real and reliable; what’s unreliable are the people involved. Internet channels often lack professional staff, and there is also a lot of misleading sales practices.
For example, insurance policies that claim to offer 6 million yuan in coverage for just 1 yuan, along with free mobile phones and additional 60,000 yuan in critical illness coverage, are not inherently wrong in their marketing strategies. However, they tend to focus on the positive aspects while avoiding more important
Thinking they could spend just 1 yuan, the insurance company would pay out 6 million (it’s like finding a gold mine right in front of them).
The free phone is only offered for special policy numbers, such as 6666 or 8888 at the end of the policy code. Moreover, if you win the prize and don’t redeem it through the notification message sent, no one will remind you to do so.
(This is another pitfall for policyholders.) The free coverage of 60,000 yuan for serious illnesses is only temporary. If you rely solely on this and have no other commercial insurance, what good will that 60,000 yuan do if you actually suffer from a serious illness? It
Currently, the state is also taking strict action against misleading practices in internet insurance sales.
So, taking everything into account, there is no problem with the platform or the product; the issue lies with the professionalism and ethical standards of the sales representatives.
It is recommended that you consider all the options carefully. In fact, many offline insurance brokerage companies offer a wider range of products, giving customers more choices and options to consider. Some of these products also provide better value for money compared to those available online.
I have personally helped 59 internet customers with underwriting offline products, enabling each of them to save between 2,000 and 3,000 yuan per year on their insurance premiums.
If anyone has any questions, feel free to communicate and exchange with me.
As a Mingya Insurance Broker with 3 years of experience in corporate management training, I have served nearly a thousand corporate clients and collaborated with over 100 insurance companies. Before purchasing insurance, I always start by understanding the client's needs and customize an insurance product tailored to their specific requirements. During the application process
Grow together with every customer throughout their entire lifetime.
I hope my answer can be of some help to the person who asked the question!
According to the definition provided by insurance regulatory authorities, internet insurance is an insurance business where policyholders can independently complete the entire application process by clicking on the relevant link.
In this process, neither the policyholder nor the insurance advisor needs to sign; all steps can be completed independently by the policyholder.
Although the process of purchasing insurance online lacks a sense of “ceremony” and there might not even be a printed paper contract, this in no way affects the validity or legal effect of the electronic contract.
This model is somewhat similar to the assembly-line process used in telemarketing. However, there is a fatal flaw with this approach to purchasing insurance: the subsequent services may not be able to keep up.
Since insurance is typically a long-term contract spanning several decades, shouldn't we carefully consider when purchasing insurance whether the “intermediary” we choose is someone who can truly be a reliable partner for us over the long term and continue to provide us with services even after many years?
